g last demystifies Gê social structure while modifying and reinterpreting some of the traditional ideas held about kinship, affiliation, and descent. Each of the seven contributors deals with a different lowland tribe, but all of them address an ideological focus on the dualistic tribal organization that is here defined as fundamental to the Gê As a collection, their work comprises a substantial revision of the hitherto undeveloped and largely ignored ethnography of Central Brazil.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBororo (Indiens). 0aBororo Indians. 0aBororó (Indiens). 0aEtnografie. 0aGeschichte Südamerikas. 0aGé (Indiens). 0aGê Indians. 0aIndianen. 0aSociale structuur. 4aBororo Indians. 4aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General. 4aTapuya Indians. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBamberger, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBamberger, Joan.1 aCrocker, J. Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrocker, J. Christopher.1 aLave, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLave, Jean.1 aMatta, Roberto da, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaybury-Lewis, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaybury-Lewis, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaybury-Lewis, Lewis.1 aMelatti, Julio Cezar.1 aMelatti, Julio Gezar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Terence S.1 aTurner, Terence S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWagley, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ada Matta, Roberto.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488o